## The Shape Nobody Expected

In 1931, a young German mathematician named Heinz Hopf discovered something astonishing about the three-dimensional sphere. He found that if you fill S³ — the set of all points at unit distance from the origin in four-dimensional space — with circles, they link together in an intricate, beautiful pattern. Every circle links with every other circle exactly once. None of them can be untangled.

This discovery, now called the **Hopf fibration**, seemed like pure mathematical whimsy at the time. What could linked circles in a four-dimensional sphere possibly have to do with the real world?

Everything, it turns out.

If our universe has the topology of S³ — and a growing body of evidence from the European Space Agency's Planck satellite suggests it might — then the Hopf fibration isn't just beautiful mathematics. It's the geometric scaffolding of electromagnetism, the topological origin of magnetic monopole quantization, and the reason fermions (the particles that make up all matter) can exist as global fields throughout the cosmos.

And now, for the first time, a computer has verified the mathematics with absolute certainty.

