## The Hopf Fibration: Where Topology Meets Physics

The Hopf fibration fills S³ with circles — technically, it's a map η : S³ → S² that sends each point on the 3-sphere to a point on the ordinary 2-sphere, and the preimage of every point is a perfect circle.

Our team formally proved the key identity that makes this work:

> **|η(z)|² = (|z₀|² + |z₁|²)²**

This elegant equation says that the norm of the Hopf map equals the square of the norm of the input. When you restrict to the unit sphere (|z₀|² + |z₁|² = 1), the image automatically lands on the unit 2-sphere (|η(z)|² = 1).

But the real magic is the **gauge symmetry**. If you rotate both coordinates by the same phase — replacing (z₀, z₁) with (e^{iθ}z₀, e^{iθ}z₁) — the Hopf map doesn't change at all. We proved this too:

> **η(e^{iθ}z₀, e^{iθ}z₁) = η(z₀, z₁)**

This invariance is precisely what physicists call a **U(1) gauge symmetry** — the mathematical structure underlying electromagnetism. The Hopf fibration isn't just a pretty pattern. It's a prototype for Maxwell's equations, living naturally inside the topology of S³.

Paul Dirac showed in 1931 that if magnetic monopoles exist, their charge must be quantized: g = n/2 for integer n. We formally verified this too. The quantization follows directly from the topology of the Hopf bundle — the first Chern number c₁ = 1 forces the minimal monopole charge to be exactly 1/2.

