## Gravitational Echoes

Perhaps the most dramatic prediction of an S³ universe involves gravitational waves.

On flat space, a gravitational wave from a binary neutron star merger radiates outward forever, growing weaker as it travels. On S³, that wave travels along a great circle and eventually comes back.

We proved three remarkable facts:

**1. Antipodal Refocusing.** On S³, the area of a sphere of geodesic radius χ is A(χ) = 4πR²sin²(χ/R). At the antipodal point (χ = πR), this area goes to zero:

> **A(πR) = 0**

The wave **refocuses** at the point diametrically opposite its source, like light passing through a lens. This isn't attenuation — it's amplification.

**2. Full-Circuit Return.** After traveling all the way around (χ = 2πR), the wave returns to its source and refocuses again:

> **A(2πR) = 0**

The universe acts as a gravitational resonant cavity, endlessly recycling wave energy.

**3. Universal Echo Timing.** The full-circuit time delay doesn't depend on where the source is — it depends only on the size of the universe:

> **Δt = 2πR/c**

If we ever detected a gravitational wave echo, a single measurement of the time delay would tell us the radius of the universe directly.

For R ≈ 100 billion light-years (the current best estimate for a closed universe), the echo time would be about 630 billion years — far longer than the current age of the universe. We won't be detecting these echoes any time soon. But the mathematical framework is in place, verified to the last logical step.

