## The Computer Doesn't Lie

All of these results — 64 theorems across four Lean 4 modules — have been formally verified by computer. This means every logical step has been checked against the foundational axioms of mathematics. There are no gaps, no hand-waving, no "the details are left as an exercise."

This matters because the mathematics of spherical universes involves subtle algebraic identities (like the Hopf map norm identity), delicate spectral calculations (like the mode counting formula), and topological arguments (like the PDS spectral selection rules) where human error is easy and consequences are significant.

The formal proofs give us something rare in theoretical physics: **absolute mathematical certainty** in the foundations. The remaining uncertainty is entirely physical — does our universe actually have S³ (or S³/Γ) topology?

That question awaits the data. The next generation of CMB experiments (CMB-S4 and LiteBIRD) will measure the low multipoles with unprecedented precision. The James Webb Space Telescope is mapping the large-scale structure of the universe in three dimensions. Future gravitational wave observatories might, in principle, detect the discrete mode structure predicted by a closed topology.

