## What Heinz Hopf Knew

When Heinz Hopf discovered his fibration in 1931, he couldn't have imagined that the linked circles filling S³ would one day be connected to the electromagnetic field, magnetic monopoles, and the topology of the cosmos itself.

But mathematics has a way of doing this — revealing hidden connections between structures that seem unrelated, and doing so with a certainty that no experiment can match.

If the universe is indeed S³, then we are all living inside Hopf's beautiful construction. Every point in space is threaded by an invisible circle of gauge symmetry. Every pair of these circles is linked, forever entangled. The large-scale structure of the cosmos is woven from the same topological thread that governs the behavior of electrons and photons.

And now, a computer has verified that the thread holds.

